{"cursor":"5737","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Frugality' is the quality of being frugal, sparing, thrifty, prudent or\neconomical in the use of consumable resources such as food, time or money, and\navoiding waste, lavishness or extravagance.\n\nIn behavioral science, frugality has been defined as the tendency to acquire\ngoods and services in a restrained manner, and resourceful use of already owned\neconomic goods and services, to achieve a longer term goal.\n","linknr":267,"url":"frugal","recorded":1362513104,"links":26,"instances":["economics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Simple living","Intentional living","Virtue","Waste management concepts","Waste reduction|*Frugality"],"headings":["Strategies","Philosophy","Corporate world","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f8/Wiktionary-logo-en.svg/37px-Wiktionary-logo-en.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f8/Wiktionary-logo-en.svg/37px-Wiktionary-logo-en.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/91/Wikiversity-logo.svg/16px-Wikiversity-logo.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["efficiency","economics"]],"members":["efficiency"],"related":["Resources","Food","Time","Money","Behavioral_science","Goal","Strategies","Waste","Habituation","Gratification","Efficiency_(economics)","Barter","Religious_Society_of_Friends","Puritan","Environmentalists","George_Fillmore_Swain","Yale_University_Press","Henry_David_Thoreau","Simple_living","Affluenza","Anti-consumerism","Capsule_wardrobe","Conspicuous_consumption","Downshifting","Financial_independence","Intentional_living","Miser","Mottainai","Over-consumption","Price_comparison_service","Simple_living","Thrifting","Frugal_engineering"]}